    • Method Detail

      • getUuid

        public UUID getUuid()
        Description copied from interface: Id
        Gets the primary key as UUID. Most data stores will use a long provided by Id.getId(). However a UUID can be used in the following scenarios:
        • Your data store uses UUIDs natively as primary key (e.g. apache cassandra supports this). In such case Id.getId() will always return Id.ID_UUID and Id.getUuid() holds the actual primary key.
        • You may need to express a link to a transient entity. Then you can temporary assign a UUID to the entity on the client and link it via such ID. On the server-side the actual UUID based Id can then be replaced with the actual ID while persisting the data.
        In other cases this method will simply return null.
        Returns:
        the primary key of the identified Entity as UUID value or null if Id.getId() is used.

      • getId

        public long getId()
        Returns:
        the primary key of the identified Entity as long value. It is only unique for a particular type of an entity. May also be Id.ID_UUID.

      • getVersion

        public long getVersion()
        Returns:
        the version of this entity. Whenever the Entity gets updated (a modification is saved and the transaction is committed), this counter is increased. The initial value of a new EntityBean is 0. The version acts as a modification counter for optimistic locking. On each update it will be verified that the version has not been increased already by another transaction. When linking an Entity (Id used as foreign key) the version can act as revision for auditing. If it is Id.VERSION_LATEST it points to the latest revision of the Entity. Otherwise it points to a specific historic revision of the Entity. Depending on the database technology (e.g. when using hibernate envers) the version and the revision can be semantically different. In such case a primary key can not directly be used as revisioned foreign key Id.

      • withType

        public GenericId<E> withType(Class<?> type)
        Parameters:
        type - the value of Id.getType(). Exact type should actually be Class<E> but this prevents simple usage. As the type can not actually be changed with this method, this should be fine.
        Returns:
        an instance of Id ensured to carry the type.

      • withLatestVersion

        public Id<E> withLatestVersion()
        Returns:
        this Id with a version of Id.VERSION_LATEST e.g. to use the Id as regular foreign key (pointing to the latest revision and not a historic revision).
